external_knowledge:
- "fallen stars" metaphorically refers to employees who have been terminated;
- "extinguished from the sky" means their employment status is "Terminated";
- "last known orbit" relates to their position in the company;
- "brightness" refers to their salary;
- "critics' final verdict on their performance" refers to their most recent performance rating;
- "within the last year" means the review date is between now and one year ago.

- "underperformance" refers to performance reviews rated below 3;
- "recently" means within the last six months;
- "frequent" indicates more than one review;
- "how poor and frequent" refers to the minimum rating and the number of reviews.

- "standard salary threshold" refers to a salary of 50,000;
- "roles" and "typical earnings" correspond to the position names and average salaries, respectively;
- "those currently working" implies the employment status is 'active'.

- "Captains of industry" metaphorically refer to employees who are actively contributing to the organization; 
- "Commanding vessels" are the shops where these employees are working; 
- "Monetary rewards" refers to the salaries of the employees; 
- "Still at the helm" indicates that the employees are currently active and not on leave or terminated;
- "Order of their largesse" means the order of their salary amount;
- "Highlighting the top ten in terms of their bounty" means limiting the results to the top ten highest salaries.

sql:
SELECT employees.name, positions.position_name
FROM employees
INNER JOIN positions ON employees.position_id = positions.position_id;

SELECT review_id, AVG(rating) AS average_rating
FROM performance_reviews
GROUP BY review_id;

SELECT shop_name, annual_sales
FROM shops
WHERE annual_sales > (SELECT AVG(annual_sales) FROM shops);

SELECT shop_name, number_of_employees
FROM shops
WHERE number_of_employees > 20;
